<TITLE> Tax laws 'to be simplified' </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 28 (bdnews24.com)  The government is taking steps to establish a more business- and investment-friendly environment in the country, law minister Shafique Ahmed said at the yearly conference of the International Business Forum of Bangladesh on Sunday. Revealing that the government is taking initiatives to remove judicial tangles and simplify tax laws, the law minister said, "Businessmen face various difficulties due to complexities in the law." "Currently, a business- and investment-friendly atmosphere is prevailing in the country. The government is taking further steps to improve the situation" he said. Various short- and long-term steps are being taken to develop the power and energy sector, he added. He also said, "I have seen in the newspaper that many children have died taking medicine produced by a certain company. Keeping this in mind, it is important to produce products that will not be a threat to people's health. The benefits of the people also need consideration along with company profits." The organisation's president Mahmudul Islam Chowdhury, in his welcome speech, said IBFB, through consultation with international specialists, has prepared a strategic plan that will play an effective role in ensuring the development of Bangladesh's economy and good governance. American ambassador James F Moriarty, Transparency International Bangladesh chairman M Hafizuddin Khan and others spoke in the programme held at the at the Dhaka Sheraton Hotel. 
